name: TITAN
review_text:
Located on the Gangtok-Chungthang road, this mesmerizing waterfall is situated 34km away from Lachung and 82km away from Gangtok. During our Sikkim Trip, we arrived at this enchanting spot around 2.30 PM while traveling from Gangtok to Lachung. Despite the rainy weather in the month of May, my friend Mukesh and I couldnt resist the urge to get out of the car and approach the falls. We took the opportunity to capture some breathtaking photos as a keepsake of our visit. Although we only stayed for about 25-30 minutes, the experience was truly awe-inspiring. The sheer force and volume of water cascading down created a tremendous roar that echoed in our ears. Additionally, the narrow road leading to the falls made our driver caution us about the frequent landslides in the area. This multi-tiered waterfall is not only one of the longest but also one of the most beautiful, with its crystal clear and ice-cold water. Curiosity got the better of me, and I couldnt resist taking a sip from the falls. To my delight, the water tasted incredibly refreshing and pure. As it flowed gracefully through the massive rocks, it passed under the sturdy steel bridge that spanned the road, adding to the picturesque scenery.
Visited on
Weekday

name: Binindita Das
review_text:
Naga Falls in Sikkim is a popular tourist destination known for its stunning beauty and accessibility. Located along the Gangtok-Chungthang road, about 34 kilometers from Lachung and 82 kilometers from Gangtok, this multi-tiered waterfall is set against a backdrop of snow-capped mountains and lush greenery. The falls are particularly impressive during the monsoon season when the water flow is at its peak. The main fall is a bit of a trek from the road, involving a rocky path, but the effort is rewarded with breathtaking views and great photo opportunities.
Visited on
Public holiday

Standing quickly in front of its massive creation, it might seem that the lack of a bridge might be of some advantage. But everything else comes before the beauty of the shower.

review_text:
=> It is located on Gangtok-Chungthang road, at a distance of 34km from Lachung and 82km from Gangtok.
=> We, during out Sikkim Trip, on the way from Gangtok to Lachung, had reached here at around 4 PM. In the month of May, it was raining there. Despite the rainfall, I alongwith my friend Mukesh got down from the car and went closer to the falls and captured some photos for memory.
=> We stayed there for 10-15 minutes but it was a terrific experience as the the force & amount of water was tremendous with the roaring sound. Moreover, the road was very narrow and our driver told that the sight was prone to frequent landslides.
=> This multi-tiered waterfall is one of the longest and the most beautiful waterfalls with crystal clean and ice-cold water. I drank the water of the fall and found very tasty and natural.

name: Ashok Kumar Mathur
review_text:
Naga Falls is a beautiful waterfall situated near Lachung in North Sikkim, on Gangtok-Chungthang road.
Naga falls is one of the longest and the scenic waterfalls with very clean and ice-cold water. It is a multi-tiered waterfall. The main fall is quite far from the main road so one needs to trek on a rocky path to get the view.
During monsoons the flow of water becomes extremely heavy and even dangerous.

name: Narayan Vedpathak
review_text:
Naga Falls is a stunning waterfall located on the Gangtok Lachen highway, in the north sikkim region. It is located at a distance of about 82 km from Gangtok. This waterfall
is a popular tourist attraction in the state of the Sikkim. One of the longest and most beautiful waterfalls, Naga Falls is a multi tiered waterfall having crystal-clear water. The fall gives a breathtaking view of the
mountains.
A must visit place .

name: Arpita Maji
review_text:
Never ever want to leave this place, it is such amazing place to enjoy and relax with the nature.iwould recommend to people who live the nature swimming one of the best place in the world.

At a distance of 34 km from Lachung and 82 km from Gangtok, Naga Falls is another beautiful waterfall situated near Lachung in North Sikkim. Situated on Gangtok-Chungthang road, it is one of the waterfalls in Sikkim and among the must visit places in Lachung.

Naga falls is one of the longest and the scenic waterfalls with very clean and ice-cold water. It is a multi-tiered waterfall. The main fall is quite far from the main road so one needs to trek on a rocky path to get the view. The place offer panoramic view of snow-caped mountains all around. During monsoons the flow of water becomes extremely heavy and even dangerous.

name: Shawon Khan
review_text:
About 21 km away from Bhim Nala Falls, the Naga Falls sits somewhere along the Gangtok - Chungthang road and is easily one of the most spectacular places to visit in Lachung. Another one of the tallest waterfalls in Sikkim, this multi-tiered cascade is veered a little ways off the beaten tracks and offers wonderful solitude and respite from the most popular sites in Lachung.

Early morning or evening spent here, amidst the wooded hills, listening to a beautiful medley of sounds that blend in with the tumultuous roar of the falls is an experience that lingers in the heart. Surrounded by the panorama of lofty mountain peaks, Naga Falls is an unmissable place to visit during your Sikkim trip.
On the way to Lachung from Ganktok, besides the national highway We found this beautiful long waves waterfall. As that time was raining, so the force & amount of water was huge & magnificent. This is the place where we found land slide and the road too narrow. ON tthe other side of the fall are stalls with excellent tea. A local dried fruit called khattu was discovered by me in one of the stalls here. According to the driver khattu is normally taken by the drivers as it keeps them awake and not fall asleep in the drive. The waterfall is rough and one can only photo shoot or dip their feet in water. Not to venture in the falls.

name: Subhajit Sil (Jit)
review_text:
Enroute to Lachen, you pass by this beautiful waterfall, NAGA WATERFALL The place is clean, and peaceful. Theres a bridge and below it is the river and the falls.
You can spend 15 mins over here, and relax yourself while on the 124KM journey from gangtok to Lachen.
This is a wonder place to take few selfies and clicks. Be sure not to bent too much on the river to avoid any accident. The water current is high and should be handled with care.
There isnt good shops near by so, you wont be having an option for snacks.
The cars can be parked free of cost on the roadside. While you can explore the nearby hills (stairs available) to climb a distance.

name: A S M Delwar Hossain Kohin
Krupasindu Sahoo
review_text: One of the biggest waterfall in Sikkim. The place is located on the way to lachung. You find so many crowd here. People around the India come here to enjoy the views. There is a steel bridge which connects people. The water is very cold but so no one take a bath here. Very enjoyable place must visit this place.

name: Pinaki Ranjan Das
review_text:
Wow. Such a beauty. Situated in Gangtok-Chungthang road. Its a very tall waterfall, got cascades too. The actual drop is very far from the road. One needs to walk/trek to reach to see the view of the first drop.
The amount of icy cold water it carries is huge, dangerous during the rainy season. Everyone can see the condition of the old bridge from the newly made bridge. This waterfall can be heard more than 4/5 kms away from the location.
The opposite side of the fall there stand the mighty hills, which is mesmerizing too.
Photos videos cant make you understand this place. You got to be there. One of the must visiting places of North Sikkim district.

name: Tanusree Roy
review_text: If you love waterfalls trekking then this is one of the best place to do it.

name: vaibhav gupta

name: Doctor Samya
review_text:
One of the Best Waterfall, I have seen in North Sikkim. Picture perfect landscape, Gigantic size, its really awesome. You can easily visit it by the roadside, towards your way to North Sikkim, like Lachen, lachung etc.
If you are a poet, a writer, an artist.... This place can give you photo realistic imaginations.

Naga falls is another cute waterfall in Sikkim state of India.
The waterfall is a bit dangerous as the river is a bit more swifter here.
The rocks are sharp and walking is dangerous. I will advise you to wear anti-slip shoes or footwear here.
Beware.. enjoy the beauty of nature while being careful.

review_text:
From the many waterfalls that are on the way to north Sikkim, this one has some place to stop by and enjoy the falls, the stream from it.

There are some stores for refreshment. One is located just below the waterfall, they also sell tea and coffee apart from the packed snacks available.

It is a good place to stop and have refreshments.

review_text: Amazing waterfall on the way to lachen.

name: Shivram Vaithiyanathan
review_text: It is one of the biggest in the region. It is located on the Gangtok Lachung Highway. One good hour can be spent here. One can walk further up to get a better view. There are stalls in here and can serve as a tea break during your drive to Lachung. Its a forest area and prone to landslides. Car parking is also a bit of a problem but manageable. Would recommend to avoid stopping by if theres too much crowd.

review_text: Naga falls is one of the first falls we visited during our Sikkim trip. You can climb up a fall for a better view but we settled in for a medium height as it still looked amazing. Feels like spending the whole day but couldnt as we had other spots to visit during the day.

name: Hariramakrishnan B
review_text: We group of friends visited in the month of april. A perfect time for visiting sikkim. The water there is very clear and cold. Please stop here and enjoy the place.. dont miss it.. we have been sitting in the rock and enjoying the flow of water.. the water is Crystal clear. Dont miss it when u plan for sikkim

name: Ankur Panchbudhe
review_text: Naga waterfall lies on the road from Gangtok to North Sikkim (Lachung/Lachen), between Mangan and Chumthang. Its probably the biggest waterfall on this way and is quite popular with tourists because unlike other falls on the way, here you can actually walk into the water and the fall itself. The stream of water is broken into 2-3 steps, which makes it go slower and hence safer. There are also a few stalls selling snacks and local food (like momos). The waterfall and the stream are beautiful and the surroundings are very scenic.

name: Nafis Anwar
review_text: In between Mangan and Chungthang in North Sikkim. Car going to Lachen and Lachung usually stops here. Our driver insisted No regular Mineral Water Bottle allowed after this point. Good for photography.

review_text: Cool view and the waterfall is mesmerizing to look.

name: saikat mukherjee
review_text:
This is one amongst the many falls that one can see on the way to Lachung from Gangtok on a trip to North Sikkim. Although not a place I would specifically recommend to visit as a standalone place, this place is definitely worth stopping on the way and enjoy the flow of the water and the surrounding landscape.
I would not recommend spending more than 5 mins at this place as there are better sights further along the way to North SIkkim.

name: Binayak Patel A50s
review_text:
Nice view

Niagara Falls (/naI'aegr@/) is the collective name for three waterfalls that straddle the international border between the Canadian province Ontario and the American state of New York. They form the southern end of the Niagara Gorge.
LocationBorder of Ontario, Canada, and New York, United StatesCoordinates43.0799degN 79.0747degWTypeCataractTotal height167 ft (51 m)Number of drops3WatercourseNiagara RiverAverage
flow rate85,000 cu ft/s (2,400 m3/s)

From largest to smallest, the three waterfalls are the Horseshoe Falls, the American Fallsand the Bridal Veil Falls. The Horseshoe Falls lies on the border of the United States and Canada[1] with the American Falls entirely on the United States side, separated by Goat Island. The smaller Bridal Veil Falls are also on the United States side, separated from the other waterfalls by Luna Island.

Located on the Niagara River, which drains Lake Erie into Lake Ontario, the combined falls form the highest flow rate of any waterfall in North America that has a vertical drop of more than 165 feet (50 m). During peak daytime tourist hours, more than six million cubic feet (168,000 m3) of water goes over the crest of the falls every minute.[2]Horseshoe Falls is the most powerful waterfall in North America, as measured by flow rate.[3]

The falls are 17 miles (27 km) north-northwest of Buffalo, New York, and 75 miles (121 km) south-southeast of Toronto, between the twin cities[citation needed] of Niagara Falls, Ontario, and Niagara Falls, New York. Niagara Falls was formed when glaciers receded at the end of the Wisconsin glaciation (the last ice age), and water from the newly formed Great Lakes carved a path through the Niagara Escarpment en route to the Atlantic Ocean.

GeologyEdit

The features that became Niagara Falls were created by the Wisconsin glaciation about 10,000 years ago. The same forces also created the North American Great Lakes and the Niagara River. All were dug by a continental ice sheet that drove through the area, deepening some river channels to form lakes, and damming others with debris.[9]Scientists argue there is an old valley, St Davids Buried Gorge, buried by glacial drift, at the approximate location of the present Welland Canal.

Aerial view of Niagara Falls, showing parts of Canada (left) and the United States (upper right)

When the ice melted, the upper Great Lakes emptied into the Niagara River, which followed the rearranged topography across the Niagara Escarpment. In time, the river cut a gorge through the north-facing cliff, or cuesta. Because of the interactions of three major rock formations, the rocky bed did not erode evenly. The top rock formation was composed of erosion-resistant limestone and Lockport dolostone. That hard layer of stone eroded more slowly than the underlying materials. The aerial photo on the right clearly shows the hard caprock, the Lockport Formation (Middle Silurian), which underlies the rapids above the falls, and approximately the upper third of the high gorge wall.

Immediately below the hard-rock formation, comprising about two thirds of the cliff, lay the weaker, softer, sloping Rochester Formation (Lower Silurian). This formation was composed mainly of shale, though it has some thin limestone layers. It also contains ancient fossils. In time, the river eroded the soft layer that supported the hard layers, undercutting the hard caprock, which gave way in great chunks. This process repeated countless times, eventually carving out the falls.

Submerged in the river in the lower valley, hidden from view, is the Queenston Formation(Upper Ordovician), which is composed of shales and fine sandstones. All three formations were laid down in an ancient sea, their differences of character deriving from changing conditions within that sea.

name: Mrunali Shamkuwar
review_text:
The sound of flowing water, the feel of cold water amidst the valleys of sikkim. This place offers relaxation between the long journey from gangtok to north sikkim. It might the longest waterfall in Sikkim with stream of water flowing and forming a pond surrounded by large rocks midway and a small bridge provided over it for smooth car movement. It also has a wooden pedestrian bridge over it.

Over all the place provide relaxation and enjoymeny for travellers and a good spot for photosession as well. Hope every travellers have a good time and clicks at this place as I had.
